summary.seg: Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 416 (hereafter CCCC MS 416) is a 12th-century copy of a popular medieval handbook for medieval clergy known as the Liber officialis. It is primarily concerned with the proper performance of the Christian mass and correct behaviours for priests and others who had dedicated their lives to the Church. The Liber officialis was composed by Amalarius of Metz (c. 775-c. 850), an important figure in Frankish royal and ecclesiastical power structures. Amalarius was appointed archbishop of Trier in 811 by Charlemagne, visited the Byzantine emperor Michael I Rhangabes at Constantinople in 813 at Charlemagne's request, and then supported Charlemagne's son Louis the Pious in power struggles following Charlemagne's death in 814. He was later served as archbishop of Lyon from 835 to 838.

CCCC MS 416 appears to have suffered significant damage and alteration since it was first made. On folio i recto there is a medieval list of the contents of the volume in what appears to be an early 13th-century English hand. It enumerates ten items, but of those only the first is still present in the volume: 'Amalarius de ecclesiasticis institucionibus' (an alternative medieval title for the Liber officialis). It is not clear when the other nine texts were lost from CCCC MS 416, but it was probably before Parker's acquisition of the volume. The book is described in Parker's Register simply as 'Amularius' and the opening words given as 'Vbi scs Augustinus' (see Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 575, p. 55), and the Register typically records the author and title of each work in manuscripts that contain multiple texts. The missing portion of CCCC MS 416 is not known to have survived; several of the missing texts are relatively rare medieval works, but none of the surviving examples of those works appear to be a match for the extant part of CCCC MS 416.

Dr Sarah Gilbert
Project Cataloguer for the Curious Cures project
Cambridge University Library

msItem.title: Medical recipe
msItem.note: Full transcription: 'Ad eos qui subito obmutescunt . Accipe semen canislingue tere distempa cum aqua benndicta. da bibere saNabr . Item ad idem . coque ... in uino et subfumiga os et nares pacientis . ualet
Written in a late 11th or early 12th century protogothic minuscule.

msItem.title: Note on the contents of the volume
msItem.note: Written in a late 16th or early 17th century hand.

msItem.title: Medieval list of the contents of the volume
msItem.note:
Full transcription:
In hoc uolumine continentur hii libri
Amalarius de ecclesiasticis institucionibus
Ieronimus de signis .xv. dierum ante diem iudicii
dicta cuiusdam sapientis de antichristo
Alcuinus de uirtutibus ad Widonem com
phisialogus de naturis bestiarum
prouerbia salomonis
Itinerarium antonii
Qualiter sanctus augustinus uenit in angliam iussu beati gregorii
Gesta apollonii tirii
Conuersio sancti eustachii

All of the texts are absent from the volume apart from the text by Amalarius described as 'De ecclesiasticis institucionibus' in the list, now more usually known as the 'Liber officialis'. This list of the contents of the volume was probably written in the late 12th or early 13th century. Above the main medieval list of the full contents of the volume there is a heading 'In hoc volumine continentur hii libri' followed by a note over an erasure written in a 15th century hand, 'Amalarius de matutinis ...
completoriis ordinibus et eorum ...'.

msItem.title: Liber officialis
msItem.author: Amalarius of Metz
msItem.explicit: Qua oratione paulus concludit ceteras orationes
msItem.note: List of 41 Chapters in Part 1 on ff. 1r-1v. List of 26 Chapters in Part 2 on ff. 49v-50r. List of 39 Chapters in Part 3 on ff. 67r-67v. List of 45 Chapters in Part 4 on ff. 106v-107r.

This copy of the Liber officialis lacks most of the typical prefatory material including both the longer autobiographical proem in which Amalarius explains how he came to write the text, and the dedicatory preface to the Frankish ruler Louis the Pious; instead it begins on f. 1v with the shorter preface which describes the purpose of the text.

supportDesc.condition: In fair condition. Folios 152 and 153 torn with significant loss of text on both leaves. Some leaves have sustained liquid damage at an unknown point in the past, but the liquid damage does not impede the legibility of the text. Some leaves made from irregularly sized and shaped parchment (e.g. f. 109), with surviving medieval repairs and evidence that the repairs were carried out prior to the copying of the text.

layout.seg: Ruled in drypoint, frame and lines. Ruled in single-column format, typically 35 lines to the page and written above top line.

handNote.p: Main text written in a late Anglo-Caroline minuscule, tending towards protogothic minuscule.

decoNote.p: Decorative initials in a simple 'Arabesque' style, typically 3-6 lines high at the beginning of major and minor divisions of the text in red or purple, some with minor acanthus frills and flourishing, e.g., the 'M' on f. 121v, or the 'F' on f. 83v.
Plain initials in red or purple typically 1-2 lines high in a simple 'Arabesque' style at the minor divisions of the text.
Rubrication (in red) at the major and minor divisions of the text.

note.p: Running numerical headings elucidating the current section of the Liber officialis present in the upper margin of most rectos. The section of the Liber officialis is written in Roman numerals toward the centre of the upper margin, and in Hindu-Arabic numerals closer to the fore edge of the upper margin, probably by two different scribes.
Unidentified pressmark at the top of f. i recto, 'F. 6.' in ink in the upper margin above the medical recipe and next to the word 'Amularius'.
Unidentified pressmark in the lower margin of f. 2r, '108' in ink.

The name Johannes Hadenham Hadenham, Johannes ' in faint ink on f. 140v in a 15th or 16th century hand. There is a small village called Haddenham about 5 miles (8 kilometres) from Ely, and Johannes perhaps had a connection to that village.

Corpus Christi College, MS 416 was catalogued as 'N.35' in Stanley's Catalogue of the manuscripts belonging to Corpus Christi College, Cambridge printed in 1722. Stanley's classification number, 'N.35' can be seen on folios i recto and 153v.
Quires numbered in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of the first recto of each quire, by a 20th-century hand.

binding.p: 21st century temporary binding (not photographed). Fully bound in a temporary binding of book-cloth over paste- or millboards. The manuscript was photographed without a binding for the Parker on the Web project (published online 2009), and the present binding was added by the Cambridge Conservation Consortium as a temporary measure after the photography was completed.
Brown Russia leather label fixed to spine (not photographed) with an adhesive, the shelfmark 'MS 416' tooled in gold on the label.

Paper pastedowns pasted over the turn-ins. Five modern paper endleaves at each end of the volume (not photographed), ff. [a]-[e] and [f]-[j]. All paper endleaves blank except f. [a] recto which has a note 'CCCC MS 416 Temporary binding' in pencil.

origin.origDate: Written in the first half of the 12th century.
origin.p: Date and place of production assigned based on palaeographical features. Date of production assigned to the first half of the 12th century by Richard Gameson in The Manuscripts of Early Norman England (c.1066-1130), no. 88.

listBibl.bibl: R. Gameson, The Manuscripts of Early Norman England (c.1066-1130) (Oxford: Published for the British Academy by Oxford University Press, 1999), no. 88

provenance.p: Given (?to Ely Cathedral Priory) by a William de Stradesete William de Stradesete : donation inscription (with unnamed beneficiary) in a ?13th-century hand on folio i recto, 'Hunc librum dedit Willelmus sacerdos de stradesete cuius memoriam cum oratione faciat qui in eo legerit' ('The priest William de Stradesete gave this book, he who reads [this book] should remember [him] with prayer'). There is a village called Stradsett in Norfolk, England, approximately 19 miles (30 kilometres) from Ely and it is possible that William may have originated from that village. No biographical details of William are known (a William Ockley William Ockley was vicar of Stradsett from 1402-?1408 but his lifespan postdates the date at which the donation inscription was written).

Partial names visible on f. 153v under handheld ultraviolet light, now badly rubbed and damaged. The names appear to be in 14th or 15th century hands. What little can be read of the names is as follows:
Johannes
Bygh...
...styfall...
Henr...
Owned by the medieval community of Ely Cathedral Priory during the 15th century, and may have entered its collection as early as the late 12th or early 13th century (see above).

The oldest significant provenance evidence for the precise location of the volume in the medieval period is the distinctive Ely pressmark (resembling a Roman majuscule numeral II, surmounted by a cross) in the outer margin of f. 1r. This confirms that the volume was part of the Ely Cathedral Priory collection by the 15th century, when these marks were added to some of its manuscripts (see CBMLC 4 for further information). Other Ely manuscripts with the mark include: Cambridge, University Library, MS Gg.1.21, f. 1r Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 44 Cambridge, Trinity College, MS O.2.1, f. 1r

Unidentified pressmark at the top of folio i recto, 'F. 6.' in ink at the top of the leaf above the medical recipe and next to the word 'Amularius'. The pressmark conforms to the Bury St Edmunds pressmark format (and that of several other religious houses), i.e., a majuscule letter followed by a Hindu-Arabic number), but the mark in CCCC MS 416 probably postdates the Bury St Edmunds pressmarking campaign by at least a century, nor is it a palaeographical match for any other Bury St Edmunds pressmarks. Further rejection of the 'F. 6.' as a Bury St Edmunds pressmark can be based on the use of an 'F' class at Bury St Edmunds being almost entirely unattested, and the Bury St Edmunds letter classes having a thematic link to the volume by either author or subject, and the letter 'F' not having an obvious relationship to the content of CCCC MS 416.
Unidentified pressmark in the lower margin of f. 2r, '108' in ink.

acquisition.p: Bequeathed to Corpus Christi College Cambridge in the will drawn up by Matthew Parker (b. 1504, d. 1575) Matthew Parker (b. 1504, d. 1575) in 1574; Parker died in 1575, and his bequest was transferred to Corpus Christi College over several years following his death.
